{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17418446","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17418446"},"attributes":{"position":3,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T10:35:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T10:35:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261514"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261514"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14173"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526953","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526953"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:27:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:27:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14173"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261514","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261514"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T10:35:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:36:42+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":7,"questionsAnswered":6,"marksTotal":6,"marksAttainable":6,"marksAttempted":6,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T10:35:40+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0,"questionsCorrect":0,"marksCorrect":0},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"14173","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14173"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.01,0.52,0.07,0.31]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6856"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103515"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6856","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6856"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14173"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85931"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15598"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18011"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18477"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18505"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19084"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20835"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36572"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36644"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36645"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103515"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old woman living in a metropolitan area presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine check-up. She has a background history of type 2 diabetes mellitus since the age of 40 years, and she is a current smoker. Her regular medications include metformin XR 1 gram twice daily. She works as an accountant and leads a sedentary lifestyle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 76/min, blood pressure 148/92 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Her BMI is 28 kg/m\u00b2 (height 156 cm, weight 70 kg). Physical examination is otherwise unremarkable. Repeat blood pressure measurements over two visits confirm persistent hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELatest blood results reveal HbA1c 7.0% (4.0-6.0), total cholesterol 5.6 mmol/L (3.9-5.5), LDL 2.6 mmol/L (0-3.4), HDL 0.8 mmol/L (1.0-2.1). Her eGFR is \u0026gt;90 mL/min (\u0026gt;90), and urine albumin-to-creatinine ratio is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first-line management for this patient, in addition to lifestyle modifications?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Commence hydrochlorothiazide","Commence glyceryl trinitrate","Commence amlodipine","Commence metoprolol","Lifestyle modifications alone"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with newly diagnosed hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus, and is a current smoker, all of which significantly increase her cardiovascular risk. Her blood pressure of 148/92 mmHg, confirmed on multiple visits. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe decision to commence antihypertensive medication should be guided by a patient\u0027s absolute cardiovascular disease (CVD) risk, in conjunction with accurate blood pressure measurements.\u00a0Cardiovascular risk can be calculated using the Australian Absolute CVD Risk Calculator. Using this tool, she is calculated to have a high 5-year cardiovascular risk of 10%. For patients at high absolute CVD risk (10% or greater over five years) antihypertensive therapy is recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELifestyle modifications alone\u003C/strong\u003E are insufficient for this patient given her high cardiovascular risk profile. While lifestyle changes (smoking cessation, weight management, regular exercise, dietary modifications) are essential components of hypertension management, this patient requires pharmacological therapy due to her diabetes, smoking status, and confirmed hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmlodipine\u003C/strong\u003E, a calcium channel blocker, is an appropriate first-line antihypertensive for this patient. They do not adversely affect glycaemic control. Other first-line options include ACE inhibitors (Angiotensin Converting Enzyme inhibitors), ARBs (Angiotensin Receptor Blockers), and thiazide diuretics. ACE inhibitors and ARBs are particularly beneficial in patients with diabetes due to their renoprotective effects. However, this patient does not have evidence of diabetic kidney disease (normal eGFR and no albuminuria), so either an ACE inhibitor or calcium channel blocker would be reasonable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydrochlorothiazide\u003C/strong\u003E, a thiazide diuretic, is a reasonable antihypertensive option but may not be the optimal first choice in patients with diabetes due to potential adverse effects on glucose metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetoprolol\u003C/strong\u003E, a beta-blocker, is not recommended as first-line therapy for uncomplicated hypertension unless there are specific indications such as coronary artery disease or heart failure. Beta-blockers may reduce insulin sensitivity and mask hypoglycaemic symptoms, making them less desirable in patients with diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlyceryl trinitrate \u003C/strong\u003Eis inappropriate as it is a short-acting medication used for angina or acute hypertensive emergencies, not for long-term blood pressure management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe choice between these agents should be individualized based on patient characteristics, comorbidities, and potential side effects. Regular follow-up and adjustment of therapy based on blood pressure response is essential.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["First-line antihypertensive therapy for patients with diabetes typically includes ACE inhibitors, ARBs, calcium channel blockers, or thiazide diuretics.","Lifestyle modifications are an essential component of hypertension management for all patients.","Cardiovascular risk assessment should guide the urgency and intensity of hypertension management."],"references":["2024 ESC Guidelines for the management of elevated blood pressure and hypertension.Eur Heart J 2024 Vol. 45 Issue 38 Pages 3912-4018","National Vascular Disease Prevention Alliance. Australian Absolute Cardiovascular Disease Risk Calculator[Internet]. Melbourne: NVDPA; [cited 2025 May 23]. Available from: https://www.cvdcheck.org.au/calculator","National Heart Foundation of Australia. Guideline for the diagnosis and management of hypertension in adults \u2013 2016 [Internet]. Melbourne: National Heart Foundation of Australia; 2016 [cited 2025 May 23]. Available from: https://assets.contentstack.io/v3/assets/blt8a393bb3b76c0ede/bltbf3d36e10b48f01f/65b0963ea933e532ae0286de/01_Hypertension-guideline-2016_WEB.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85931"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14173"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85931"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-23T11:34:07+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-05T08:40:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6856"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103515"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"gro